Thanks @Jhsmit.

@Pitje06: Currently only reals are supported, since typically your fit will be performed using `least_sq`, which assumes real values. Thinking about it now, I think this can be extended by changing (f - y)^2 to |f - y|^2, where |f - y| denotes the magnitude of the complex residual. Should be plug and play. 

I also saw the other day that `scipy` has `complex_ode`, which is good to have as well since those are quite common in physics. However, I'm boycotting this particular object because it was modeled on `ode`, which was designed by a madman. It's fine for a specific problem, but writing a general wrapper for it is literally impossible, which is why I switched to `odeint`. I think that in the future an ODE specific package needs to wrapped to make this feature way more powerful.

Hi @eddies, if your target is the web you are not going to want `fibers` or `sqlite3`, they aren't designed to be used in a browser and daff only uses then on the command-line.

The https://github.com/paulfitz/daff-web repo has a daff.js with is usable from a raw web environment.  I could well imagine the exports checks blowing up in something like webpack, that part is messy and delicate and everybody's hacks interfere with each other.

Someone asked recently (private email) about getting daff working from Google App scripts, and that also involved fiddling with exports stuff.  Here were steps that worked to get to a minimal first working test in that context, just in case they help in debugging here.

  * grab daff.js from github https://github.com/paulfitz/daff/releases/tag/v1.3.16
  * remove the first line of this file (starts with a #)
  * wrap it all up in a function like this:

```js
function init_daff() {
  var exports = {};
  function require(x) {
    return {};
  }
  var module = 1;
  
  // daff.js code goes here, without first line

   return exports;
}
```

I could then test if from a separate function:

```js
function myFunction() {
  var daff = init_daff();
  var data1 = [
    ['Country','Capital'],
    ['Ireland','Dublin'],
    ['France','Paris'],
    ['Spain','Barcelona']
  ];
  var data2 = [
    ['Country','Code','Capital'],
    ['Ireland','ie','Dublin'],
    ['France','fr','Paris'],
    ['Spain','es','Madrid'],
    ['Germany','de','Berlin']
  ];
  var table1 = new daff.TableView(data1);
  var table2 = new daff.TableView(data2);
  var alignment = daff.compareTables(table1,table2).align();
  var data_diff = [];
  var table_diff = new daff.TableView(data_diff);
  var flags = new daff.CompareFlags();
  var highlighter = new daff.TableDiff(alignment,flags);
  highlighter.hilite(table_diff);
  Browser.msgBox('Greetings', table_diff, Browser.Buttons.OK);  // <-- the simplest way I could find to see something in Google Scripts, obviously not what you will want
}
```

Will take a look at your specific webpack case when I get a chance (might be a while).

