@nelson-liu I made exactly the same reasoning about Keras API. Still, I think it's simply counterintuitive that ``patience = 0`` disables  early stopping and the fact that other libraries behave differently only add to that. Furthermore, there's not a strict need to reserve zero for that function.

@schmmd Yes, I find that confusing too and your proposal sounds reasonable to me. If I had to implement early-stopping from scratch, I'd define ``patience`` as the max number of (consecutive) epochs with no improvement one can tolerate **without** stopping the training, so that the training is stopped after ``patience + 1`` unsuccessful epochs. In other words, it'd be the max number of consecutive postponements of early stopping. This way:
* ``patience == 0`` means what it suggests: no patience, stop at the first epoch with no improvement;
* ``patience == 1`` means you can tolerate 1 epoch with no improvement, but not 2 consecutive ones.

Anyway, this issue is just a minor detail. I would have never opened it if I hadn't reviewed https://github.com/allenai/allennlp/pull/1246 (which crashes for ``patience == 0``), given that I always use ``patience >= 2`` in practice. Whatever decision will be taken about it, it'll be fine as long as it is well-documented.

